# serializer version: 1
# name: test_help_snapshot[bpd completion]
  '''
  Usage: bpd completion [OPTIONS] {bash|zsh|fish}
  
    Print a shell completion script.
  
    Examples:     bpd completion bash >> ~/.bashrc     eval "$(bpd completion
    zsh)"
  
  Options:
    -h, --help  Show this message and exit.
  
  '''
# ---
# name: test_help_snapshot[bpd config get]
  '''
  Usage: bpd config get [OPTIONS] {logging.file|logging.file_level|logging.format|
                        logging.level|output.color|output.format|token}
  
    Show a resolved config value and where it came from.
  
    The token is masked and resolves from flag/env only. Examples:     bpd config
    get output.color     bpd config get logging.level --json     bpd config get
    token
  
  Options:
    -o, --output [text|json|markdown]
                                    Output format. [default: text]
    --json                          Shorthand for --output json.
    --output-file FILE              Write results to a file instead of stdout
                                    (format set by --output).
    -v, --verbose                   Increase log verbosity (-vv for debug).
    -q, --quiet                     Suppress non-essential stderr output.
    --log-level [debug|info|warning|error|critical]
                                    Explicit console log level (overrides -v/-q).
    --log-file TEXT                 Enable rotating file logging (PATH optional;
                                    default: XDG state).
    --no-color                      Disable colored output.
    --config FILE                   Path to a TOML config file (overrides layered
                                    discovery).
    --token TEXT                    Py Personal Access Token (overrides
                                    $BPD_TOKEN). Never stored.
    --no-input                      Never prompt; fail instead (for scripts/CI).
    -h, --help                      Show this message and exit.
  
  '''
# ---
# name: test_help_snapshot[bpd config init]
  '''
  Usage: bpd config init [OPTIONS]
  
    Create or update the config file with guided prompts.
  
    Asks (on stderr, so stdout stays pipe-safe) for the most common settings,
    offering the currently resolved values as defaults, then writes them to the
    TOML config file. Secrets are never written — the token stays in --token /
    $BPD_TOKEN. Examples:
  
        bpd config init     bpd config init --yes       # accept current values,
        no prompts     bpd config init --dry-run   # preview, write nothing
  
  Options:
    --dry-run                       Show what would change; write nothing.
    -y, --yes                       Skip confirmation prompts (for scripts/CI).
    -o, --output [text|json|markdown]
                                    Output format. [default: text]
    --json                          Shorthand for --output json.
    --output-file FILE              Write results to a file instead of stdout
                                    (format set by --output).
    -v, --verbose                   Increase log verbosity (-vv for debug).
    -q, --quiet                     Suppress non-essential stderr output.
    --log-level [debug|info|warning|error|critical]
                                    Explicit console log level (overrides -v/-q).
    --log-file TEXT                 Enable rotating file logging (PATH optional;
                                    default: XDG state).
    --no-color                      Disable colored output.
    --config FILE                   Path to a TOML config file (overrides layered
                                    discovery).
    --token TEXT                    Py Personal Access Token (overrides
                                    $BPD_TOKEN). Never stored.
    --no-input                      Never prompt; fail instead (for scripts/CI).
    -h, --help                      Show this message and exit.
  
  '''
# ---
